sian republic would be grounded on monotheism, while also insisting that the new nation would protect diverse religious practice. The essays in Religious Pluralism in Indonesia explore how the state, civil society groups, and individual Indonesians have experienced the attempted integration of minority and majority religious practices and faiths across the archipelagic state over the more than half century since Pancasila. The chapters in Religious Pluralism in Indonesia offer analyses of contemporary phenomena and events; the changing legal and social status of certain minority groups; inter-faith relations; and the role of Islam in Indonesia's foreign policy. Amidst infringements of human rights, officially recognized minorities—Protestants, Catholics, Hindus, Buddhists and Confucians—have had occasional success advocating for their rights through the Pancasila framework. Others, from Ahmadi and Shi'i groups to atheists and followers of new religious groups, have been left without safeguards, demonstrating the weakness of Indonesia's institutionalized "pluralism."  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aPancasilavCongresses. 0aReligion and statezIndonesiaxHistoryy20th centuryvCongresses. 0aReligionsxRelationsxHistoryy20th centuryvCongresses. 0aReligious pluralismzIndonesiaxHistoryy20th centuryvCongresses. 0aReligious tolerancezIndonesiaxHistoryy20th centuryvCongresses. 4aAsian Studies. 4aIslamic Religion & Studies. 4aReligious Studies. 7aHISTORY / Asia / Southeast Asia.2bisacsh  aReligious Intolerance in Indonesia, Islamism/Fundamentalism, Minority oppression in Indonesia, Islamist majoritarianism, Islam in Indonesia’s foreign policy.1 aAragon, Lorraine V., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDuncan, Christopher R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/v